label("$C$", C, SW);
[/asy]

Also, the midpoint of $AB$ lies on the line $y = x + 3,$ so
\[\frac{b+d}{2} = \frac{a+c}{2} + 3 = \frac{60}{2} = 30.\]Hence, $a + b + c + d = 60 + 6 = 66.$

By the Pythagorean Theorem, $AB = \sqrt{a^2 + b^2} = \sqrt{c^2 + d^2} = 60.$  Squaring both sides of $b + d = a + c + 6,$ we get
\[a^2 + 2ab + b^2 + 2ac + 2bd + c^2 + 2cd + d^2 = 4(a + b + c + d) + 36.\]Then $2ab + 2ac + 2bd + 2cd = 2(a + b + c + d) + 3.$  Substituting $a + b + c + d = 66,$ we get $ab + ac + bd + cd = 35.$

Then
\begin{align*}
[ABC]^2 &= s(s - a)(s - b)(s - c) \\
&= \left( \frac{a + b + c}{2} \right) \left( \frac{a + b - c}{2} \right) \left( \frac{a - b + c}{2} \right) \left( \frac{-a + b + c}{2} \right) \\
&= \frac{1}{16} (2ab + 2ac + 2bd + 2cd)(-2ab + 2ac - 2bd + 2cd) \\
&\quad \cdot (2ab - 2ac - 2bd + 2cd)(-2ab - 2ac + 2bd + 2cd) \\
&= \frac{1}{16} (2(a + b + c + d) + 3)(-2(a + b + c + d) + 3) \\
&\quad \cdot (2(a - b + c - d) + 3)(-2(a + b - c - d) + 3) \\
&= \frac{1}{16} (135)(-129)(19)(-23) \\
&= 5 \cdot 3^3 \cdot 7 \cdot 11^2 \\
&= 3465^2.
\end{align*}Therefore, $[ABC] = \boxed{3465}.$

The set of points that are inside or within one unit of a rectangular parallelepiped is shown below.

[asy]
import three;

size(180);
currentprojection = perspective(6,3,2);

triple A = (0,0,0), B = (3,0,0), C = (3,4,0), D = (0,4,0), P = (0,0,5), Q = (3,0,5), R = (3,4,5), S = (0,4,5);
draw(B--C--R--Q--B);
draw(A--D--S--P--A);
draw(A--B--Q--P--A--D--C--B);
draw(C--D--S--R--C);
draw(P--Q,dashed);
draw(D--S,dashed);
draw(A--P,dashed);
draw(B--Q,dashed);
draw(C--R,dashed);
label("$3$", (B + C)/2, N);
label("$4$", (C + D)/2, E);
label("$5$", R + (0,0,1), N);
[/asy]

The volume of the rectangular parallelepiped is $3 \cdot 4 \cdot 5 = 60.$  The volume of the set of points that are inside or within one unit of the rectangular parallelepiped is equal to the original volume, plus the volumes of the six rectangular parallelepipeds that extend out one unit from the faces.  Each of these parallelepipeds has volume equal to the product of the areas of two adjacent faces, which is $3 \cdot 4,$ $4 \cdot 5,$ or $3 \cdot 5.$  Thus, the volume of the set of points is $60 + 2(3 \cdot 4 + 4 \cdot 5 + 3 \cdot 5) + 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 4 = 220.$  Therefore, $m+n+p=220+1+2=\boxed{223}.$

We can start by placing the box on a coordinate system, with one corner at the origin and edges parallel to the axes. Then the set of points within one unit of the box is the union of the box and eight congruent frustums, one for each vertex of the box. Each frustum can be obtained by cutting off a corner of the box with a plane perpendicular to one of its three faces, as shown below.

[asy]
import three;

size(200);
currentprojection = perspective(6,3,2);

triple A = (0,0,0);
triple B = (3,0,0);
triple C = (3,4,0);
triple D = (0,4,0);
triple E = (0,0,5);
triple F = (3,0,5);
triple G = (3,4,5);
triple H = (0,4,5);

draw(B--C--G--F--B);
draw(A--D--H--E--A);
draw(A--B,dashed);
draw(D--C,dashed);
draw(H--G,dashed);
draw(E--F,dashed);

label("$3$", (B + C)/2, N);
label("$4$", (C + G)/2, E);
label("$5$", (G + F)/2, N);
label("$x$", (0,0,2.5), W);
label("$x$", (0,2,0), W);
label("$x$", (1.5,0,0), S);
[/asy]

The frustum shown above can be obtained by cutting off a corner of the box with a plane perpendicular to the face $ABCD.$ The distance from the corner $A$ to the plane is $x = 1$ (since the edge length of the frustum is $2$), and the area of face $ABCD$ is $3\cdot 4 = 12.$ Therefore, the volume of this frustum is
\begin{align*}
&\frac{1}{3}\cdot 12\cdot (1^2 + 1\cdot 2 + 2^2) \\
&\qquad= \frac{1}{3}\cdot 12\cdot 7 \\
&\qquad= 28.
\end{align*}
Since there are eight congruent frustums, the total volume of all the frustums is $8\cdot 28 = 224.$ The volume of the box is $3\cdot 4\cdot 5 = 60,$ so the volume of the set of points within one unit of the box is $60 + 224 = 284.$ Thus, $m+n+p=284+1+7=\boxed{292}.$

